<font color="#FF0000">REFLECTIONS</font><br>
<tt>Thu Jan 15 13:20:00 US/Eastern 1998
</tt><p>
The time in Vietnam was consumed by many thoughts.  None of those thoughts involved , why am I here, what is wrong with my government, or who are the communists.<br><br>
I was focused on doing a good job and helping my Bros as much as possible.  I can't even count the times I violated the rules to help a bro.  I went where I was prohibited, did things I couldn't report, exceeded the limits of the aircraft, and recovered below bingo fuel so many times I lost count.  All wrong, but right for the men who needed me.<br><br>
I worried about staying alive, my ability to extract the maximum from my machine and never letting the Bros down, what was for the next meal, why the Booze was so bad, and of course I was never paid enough.<br><br>
What was reprehensible?  Always feeling like I could have done more and who paid the price because I didn't. When the need was too many having to choose who you helped and who you didn't. Being deep in the gulf, outside Haiphong, when the war ended and two F-4s mid aired celebrating the end.  During the SAR we only saved two.  I will never forget that.  What a waste.<br><br>
All my questions come when I have time to reflect.  Those occupied with the war didn't have time to think about ideology and politics.  At least we didn't. It is only after returning did we get the cram course.  Crammed directly in our face.<br><br>
The only regrets these days are those choices I made and wondering if I was right.
<p><code>--   (SW) </code><p>


